    '**Circuit Switcher:**\n- A hybrid device combining an interrupter (SF6 or vacuum) with an isolating switch\n- Lower cost than a full circuit breaker (40–60% of breaker cost)\n- Lower interrupting rating (typically 8–25 kA vs. 40–63 kA for breakers)\n- Slower operating time (5–8 cycles vs. 3 cycles)\n- Designed primarily for transformer protection (switching transformer magnetizing current and clearing transformer faults)\n- Cannot handle bus faults or line faults with high fault currents\n- Includes built-in disconnect function — no separate disconnect switch needed\n\n**Circuit Breaker:**\n- Full fault-interrupting device rated for all system fault duties\n- Higher cost, higher capability\n- Faster operation (3 cycles)\n- Can handle any fault within its rating — bus, line, transformer\n- Requires separate disconnect switches for visible isolation\n\n**When to use a circuit switcher:**\n- Transformer protection where available fault current is within switcher rating\n- Cost-sensitive installations\n- Distribution substations where full breaker capability is unnecessary\n- Cannot be used for line protection or bus protection',
    ['circuit-breaker', 'circuit-switcher', 'switching']
