    'What is a single bus configuration? What are its advantages and limitations?',
    '**Single Bus:**\n- All circuits (lines, transformers) connect to a single bus through their respective breakers\n- The simplest and lowest-cost bus arrangement\n\n**Advantages:**\n- Simple design, easy to understand and operate\n- Lowest cost — minimum number of breakers and disconnects\n- Small footprint\n\n**Limitations:**\n- **Any bus fault de-energizes the ENTIRE substation** — all circuits are lost\n- **Maintenance of any breaker requires de-energizing its circuit** — no way to transfer to another bus\n- **No flexibility** — a single point of failure (the bus itself)\n\n**Where used:**\n- Small distribution substations with low reliability requirements\n- Temporary or construction substations\n- Locations where load can be back-fed from other substations during bus outage\n\n**Enhancement:** Adding a bus sectionalizer (normally closed breaker that splits the bus) improves reliability — a bus fault only loses half the bus. This is called a "sectionalized single bus" and is common at distribution substations.',
