    '**Double Bus Single Breaker:**\n- Two independent buses (Bus 1 and Bus 2) with a bus-tie breaker connecting them\n- Each circuit has one breaker and two disconnect switches — one to each bus\n- Any circuit can be connected to either bus via its disconnect switches\n\n**Operation:**\n- Normal: All circuits on Bus 1 (or split between buses). Bus tie may be open or closed.\n- Transfer: Move a circuit from Bus 1 to Bus 2 by opening its Bus 1 disconnect and closing its Bus 2 disconnect (with bus tie closed to avoid interruption)\n- Bus maintenance: Transfer all circuits to the other bus, then de-energize the empty bus for maintenance\n\n**Advantages:**\n- Flexibility to move circuits between buses\n- Either bus can be taken out for maintenance without losing circuits\n- Bus fault only loses circuits on the faulted bus (if bus tie is open)\n\n**Limitations:**\n- A breaker failure still loses its circuit (no bypass)\n- Requires careful disconnect switch operation (interlocking essential)\n- Higher cost than single bus (two buses, bus tie breaker, extra disconnects)\n\n**Where used:** Medium-importance substations, distribution substations needing bus maintenance flexibility.',
