// ==================== SET 6: Surge Protection & Grounding ====================
const set6 = [
  card(
    'How do metal-oxide surge arresters (MOSAs) work?',
    '**Metal-Oxide Surge Arresters (MOSAs)** are the primary defense against lightning and switching surges in substations. They protect equipment insulation (transformers, breakers, bus) from voltage spikes that exceed insulation capability.\n\n**How they work:**\n- Made of zinc oxide (ZnO) varistor discs stacked in a porcelain or polymer housing\n- ZnO is a semiconductor with a highly nonlinear voltage-current characteristic:\n  - At **normal system voltage:** Very high impedance → negligible leakage current (< 1mA). Arrester is essentially invisible to the system.\n  - During a **surge (overvoltage):** Impedance drops dramatically → arrester conducts thousands of amperes, clamping the voltage to a safe level\n  - After surge passes: impedance returns to high state immediately\n- No gap to spark over (unlike older silicon carbide arresters with series gaps)\n- Continuous duty — always connected, always ready\n\n**Key ratings:**\n- **MCOV (Maximum Continuous Operating Voltage):** Must exceed the maximum continuous system voltage at the arrester location\n- **Duty cycle rating:** Nominal voltage class (e.g., 108kV for 138kV system)\n- **Discharge voltage:** The clamping voltage at a specified discharge current (e.g., 10kA, 8/20μs)\n- **Energy absorption capability:** kJ/kV of MCOV — must handle the energy of expected surges\n\n**Failure mode:** If energy exceeds capability, ZnO discs crack or melt → short circuit → arrester ground lead fuse operates to prevent sustained fault.',
    ['surge-protection', 'arrester', 'MOV', 'lightning']
  ),
  card(
    'Where should surge arresters be installed in a substation?',
    '**Installation locations (in order of priority):**\n\n**1. Transformer terminals (highest priority):**\n- Installed directly on or as close as possible to transformer bushings (both HV and LV sides)\n- Transformers are the most expensive and longest-lead-time equipment — protection is critical\n- Lead length from arrester to transformer terminal must be minimized — every foot of lead adds inductance that increases the voltage at the protected terminal (L × di/dt)\n\n**2. Overhead line entrances (aerial terminations):**\n- Where overhead lines enter the substation — the primary path for lightning surges\n- Lightning strikes a transmission line → traveling wave propagates to the substation at near-light speed\n- Arresters at the entrance provide the first stage of protection\n\n**3. Bus terminations and cable terminations:**\n- At transitions from overhead to underground cable (cable has lower BIL than air-insulated equipment)\n- At major bus junctions and open-ended bus (voltage doubling effect at open ends)\n\n**4. Other equipment:**\n- Circuit breakers (especially when open — surge can appear across open contacts)\n- Capacitor banks, reactor banks\n- Instrument transformers (especially CCVTs)\n\n**Installation rules:**\n- Mount as close to protected equipment as physically possible\n- Keep lead lengths (both line-side and ground-side) as short as possible — ideally < 2 feet\n- Ground lead connects directly to the station ground grid\n- Arrester ground must be bonded to the equipment tank/frame ground',
    ['surge-protection', 'arrester', 'installation', 'substation']
  ),
  card(
    'How does BIL coordination with surge arrester ratings work?',
    '**BIL Coordination** ensures that surge arresters clamp transient voltages to a level safely below the insulation withstand capability of the protected equipment.\n\n**The protection chain:**\n1. Equipment has a rated BIL (e.g., transformer at 138kV has BIL = 550kV)\n2. Surge arrester has a protective level — the maximum voltage it allows during a surge (e.g., 345kV at 10kA discharge)\n3. The **protective margin** = (BIL - Protective Level) / Protective Level × 100%\n4. Minimum recommended margin: **20% for lightning**, **15% for switching surges** (IEEE C62.22)\n\n**Example coordination:**\n- 138kV transformer: BIL = 550kV\n- Arrester discharge voltage at 10kA = 345kV\n- Margin = (550 - 345) / 345 × 100% = 59% ✓ (well above 20% minimum)\n\n**Factors that reduce the effective margin:**\n- **Lead length:** Each foot of arrester lead adds ~1.6kV per kA/μs of surge steepness\n- **Separation distance:** Voltage increases with distance between arrester and equipment (traveling wave reflections)\n- **Aging:** ZnO disc degradation over decades slightly increases clamping voltage\n\n**Standard BIL levels (IEEE C57.12.00):**\n| System kV | Standard BIL (kV) |\n|-----------|-------------------|\n| 15 | 95/110 |\n| 34.5 | 200 |\n| 69 | 350 |\n| 138 | 550/650 |\n| 230 | 900/1050 |\n| 345 | 1300 |\n\n**Reduced BIL** can be specified when high-quality surge protection (close-mounted, low-lead-length arresters) is guaranteed.',
    ['surge-protection', 'BIL', 'coordination', 'insulation']
  ),
  card(
    'What is a substation grounding (ground grid) system and how is it designed?',
    '**The ground grid** is a network of buried bare copper conductors forming a mesh beneath and around the substation, connected to all equipment frames, structures, and neutral points.\n\n**Purpose:**\n- Provide a low-impedance path for fault current to return to the source\n- Limit **step potential** (voltage between a person\'s feet) and **touch potential** (voltage between hand on grounded equipment and feet) to safe levels during faults\n- Ensure reliable operation of ground-fault protective relays\n- Dissipate lightning current safely\n\n**Design per IEEE 80:**\n- **Grid conductor:** Typically 4/0 AWG bare copper (or larger for high fault current stations)\n- **Mesh spacing:** 10–30 feet between parallel conductors (closer spacing = lower touch potential)\n- **Depth:** 18–30 inches below grade\n- **Ground rods:** 8–10 foot copper-clad steel rods driven at grid intersections and equipment foundations, extending below the grid to reach lower-resistivity soil\n- **Perimeter conductor:** Surrounds the entire substation footprint\n\n**Design calculations:**\n- Measure soil resistivity (Wenner 4-pin method)\n- Calculate maximum grid current during worst-case fault\n- Compute mesh voltage and step voltage\n- Compare against tolerable limits (based on body weight, fault clearing time, surface material)\n\n**Surface material:** 4–6 inches of crushed rock (3000–5000 Ω·m resistivity) over native soil dramatically increases tolerable touch and step voltages by adding resistance between a person\'s feet and the ground.\n\n**Grid resistance target:** Typically < 1Ω for transmission substations, < 5Ω for distribution.',
    ['grounding', 'ground-grid', 'safety', 'IEEE-80']
  ),
  card(
    'Compare solidly grounded, resistance grounded, and ungrounded power systems.',
    '**Solidly Grounded:**\n- Transformer neutral connected directly to ground with no intentional impedance\n- **Fault current:** High (thousands to tens of thousands of amperes) — limited only by system and transformer impedance\n- **Advantages:** Low overvoltages during ground faults (L-N voltage on unfaulted phases stays near normal), easy fault detection, allows use of standard protective devices\n- **Disadvantages:** High fault current causes significant damage at fault point, high step/touch potentials\n- **Where used:** Utility distribution (required by NEC for services >1000V with >150V to ground), 480Y/277V systems, most LV systems\n\n**Resistance Grounded (Low or High):**\n- Resistor inserted between neutral and ground\n- **Low-resistance:** 100–1000A ground fault current. Allows quick relay detection and tripping. Standard for 5–15kV industrial systems.\n- **High-resistance:** <10A ground fault current. System can continue running with a single ground fault (alarm, don\'t trip). Current limited to ≈ system capacitive charging current.\n- **Advantages:** Reduced fault damage, reduced arc flash energy, controlled fault current\n- **Where used:** Industrial MV systems, data center MV distribution, process plants\n\n**Ungrounded:**\n- No intentional ground connection. System "floats."\n- Single ground fault: no fault current path → system continues operating (alarm only)\n- **Danger:** Arcing ground faults cause transient overvoltages up to 5-6× normal L-N voltage → insulation failure → escalation to multi-phase fault\n- Largely abandoned for new installations due to overvoltage risk. Replaced by high-resistance grounding which provides the same continuity benefit without the overvoltage hazard.',
    ['grounding', 'system-grounding', 'resistance-grounding', 'neutral']
  ),
  card(
    'What are shield wires on transmission lines and how do they protect against lightning?',
    '**Shield wires (overhead ground wires / OHGW / static wires)** are grounded conductors strung above the phase conductors on transmission line structures.\n\n**How they protect:**\n1. **Lightning interception:** The shield wire is positioned to intercept lightning strikes that would otherwise hit the phase conductors. It creates a protective "shadow" zone below it — the shielding angle (typically 20–30° from vertical) defines this zone.\n2. **Current diversion:** When lightning strikes the shield wire, current flows through the wire and down the tower/pole grounds to earth — bypassing the phase conductors entirely.\n3. **Induced voltage reduction:** Even if lightning doesn\'t strike the line directly, nearby strikes induce voltages. The grounded shield wire reduces induced voltages on phase conductors by electromagnetic coupling.\n\n**Design considerations:**\n- **Number of shield wires:** One for lower voltage lines, two for EHV (345kV+) to achieve adequate shielding angle on wide structures\n- **Material:** Galvanized steel (standard), ACSR, or Alumoweld. Increasingly: OPGW (Optical Ground Wire) — contains fiber optic cables for communication AND serves as shield wire.\n- **Tower footing resistance:** Must be low (<10–25Ω) for effective lightning protection. High footing resistance causes "back-flashover" — the tower voltage rises so high during a strike that it arcs BACK from the tower/ground wire to the phase conductor.\n\n**At the substation:** Shield wires terminate at the dead-end structures. Lightning masts (tall grounded poles) protect equipment within the substation yard, providing a cone of protection (per IEEE 998 rolling sphere method or electrogeometric model).',
    ['surge-protection', 'shield-wire', 'lightning', 'transmission']
  ),
];

// ==================== SET 7: MV Switchgear to 480V Panels ====================
